@Ms_Mayfield I was so inspired when I saw this.

Idk, I was just really impressed with her journey. That’s how I want my connections to look like. She fully experienced it, enforced her boundaries, communicated clearly, and gracefully moved on— not wasting her time nor his. Dope.

However, I love how she made a contract w/HERSELF and said, when it starts to hurt, I’m moving on. That’s some dope ass self awareness because what’s yours comes easy. You don’t have to fight for it or convince it to stay and treat you well. That’s some amazing self-prio as well.
Just because that connection wasn’t meant for long term, doesn’t mean it want important or didn’t happen. It’s a season that is still a part of my story. That person is still important to me.
I want to be weak in the knees sometimes. I want to cry and be emotional while processing before stanning up. 😂 And thats okay. It’s a part of being soft and enjoying the experience overall.

I really love how she allowed herself to be sad and to mourn what could have been. That’s the part that’s so impressive to me. She’s operating in her feminine energy and she’s not stoic about ending a connection she allows herself to feel the disappointment.

I love how she was self aware and stuck to her guns and communicated her needs with this guy. She didn’t have any negativity towards him personally for having his own. She didn’t try to manipulate him into chasing her. She recognized he wasn’t for her and gracefully moved on.

I want to feel all the feels. I want to be excited about meeting someone new. I want to enjoy their company. At the same time, I need to learn to adhere to my own timeline and boundaries (and everyone’s TLs and boundaries are different).

With that, comes a lot of isolation because baby... it's rough. It hurts, you lash out, you rebel, you do things you don't understand until you have a therapy session lol, you test newly set boundaries, you cry, a lot. It's wild.

It's not a process that can be shared with friends and family, it's a burden that is fully your own and mostly supported by your healing tribe (mostly my therapist and doctors). I appreciate the support that was given, to the extent it could be, but this journey was was mine.

The past two years have been very sacred to me. The process of realizing and becoming your authentic self is so traumatic and very personal. It's the stripping away of comfort and bad habits. It's being very transparent and honest with yourself and being fully naked and ashamed.

Millennials love psycho-buzzwords. Lol We did a lot to pioneer mental health in our gen but the way we take words and concepts and run with them can be annoying… me included. I want to make these concepts work for me, without making others responsible for my experience.

Anyway, thinking of things this way has made it so much easier to develop a model for relationships and boundaries with myself, personally and professionally. I can vet people and opportunities easier and it’s helped me in my journey to become as self-aware as possible.

From there, it’s my job to respect how they expect to be treated and remember that going forward. If I didn’t do that, it’s their job to protect themselves and determine how they would interact with me moving forward, if at all.

If that person were looking at boundaries as a contract with themselves they wouldn’t have made me the responsible party but instead put the responsibility on themselves. It was their job to communicate to me their contract with themselves, giving me the opportunity to respond.

I once violated someone’s boundaries accidentally and was painted out to be a bad guy. Thing is, those boundaries were never communicated to me; however, I was still expected to abide by them. So, as the offending party, the onus was on me to uphold a boundary I was unaware of.

It’s such a slightly different way to look at it but really impactful to me. It takes the power away from others and puts it my hands. If that’s how you operate, that’s fine; however, it doesn’t fit how I expect to be treated based on my contract with myself.

I think that’s were a lot of conflict with others arise. We expect people to be aware and respect our boundaries but tbh, our boundaries are for us to communicate to others and guide how WE respond to the violation of our boundaries. The onus is not on the violating party but us.
My therapist really opened my mind on the concept of boundaries. We often like to think of them as guidelines for how others should treat us but they are really contracts with ourselves.

The ridiculous thing is that when I was younger I thought this part of the process of not overthinking was being "mean" because there is no room to be "nice". lmao Whole-time being "nice" is just having weak boundaries but that's neither here nor there.

If you're upset with me but you don't tell me, your offense is not a factor. Your perception of me is not for me to own, it's yours, so yeah, you guessed it! It's not a factor. lol Etc.

Whatever is not a factor is not considered when I'm moving through life or making decisions. https://t.co/CIaZ2zNQIv

What is my truth right now? What are the facts? That's all I have to worry about. 

....That's wild to me as an overthinker! lmao I'm still shocked at how simple life is. lol

So, If you don't communicate that you want me in your life (verbally or through actions), you aren't a factor. If my job isn't attempting to advance my career, it's not a factor. The fears I have about my family's health/wellbeing are nonexistent, so it isn't a factor.

It's such a freeing concept, although it may come naturally to others and seem super simple. As an overthinker, this was such a fucking "aha!" moment. The anxiety of everyday life (and even the anxiety from life-altering decisions) was eased so much.

I used to drive myself crazy trying to predict the outcome of each and every decision I made. Obviously, I can't effectively do that because I don't know the future. TBH, all this did was influence me to "play it safe" and miss out on a lot of good opportunities.

Another thing I've practiced not doing is attempting to predict regret and possible negative effects that MAY happen as a result of a decision. My therapist called these "two-door decisions". A decision that could have two possible outcomes-- these are the ones we overthink.

I ask myself DAILY, "What action is available to me to take right now, in this moment?" I've stopped allowing my imagination to run wild with "what ifs", as well as letting those "what ifs" influence my present decisions.

The Scorpio in me is a bit controlling when it comes to my life story but I can't have control over things that are not tangible or available to me in this very moment. So a wow moment for me was to just move with the facts. Move with what I presently have and know as fact.

A gem I learned in therapy (that has helped me immensely as an overthinker) is to only deal in the facts. Hypotheticals and trying to factor in the maybes or possibilities are not reality and only induce anxiety.
